The biggest mistake people will make when reading this BRD is thinking AAMS is an AI chatbot.
It isn't.
AAMS is basically a smart virtual Technical Support Agent that sits in front of your alert queue 24/7. It watches alerts, investigates them, decides what to do, and either closes them or routes them to the right team.
The Problem AAMS Is Trying to Solve
Today the process looks like this:
Monitoring tool generates an alert.
Alert creates a ticket in Salesforce.
TSA opens ticket manually.
TSA checks logs.
TSA decides:
Real issue?
False alert?
Just informational?
Needs escalation?
TSA updates ticket.
TSA closes or routes ticket.
The challenge is:
Around 100 alerts every day.
Only 6 TSAs across 3 shifts.
Many alerts are false alarms or informational.
Engineers spend time checking alerts that don't require action.
Some alerts need re-checks after 30–60 minutes and people forget them.
What AAMS Does in Simple Words
Imagine a junior support engineer who:
✅ Never sleeps
✅ Never forgets
✅ Reads SOPs instantly
✅ Reads old RCA documents
✅ Checks logs automatically
✅ Documents everything
✅ Escalates only when required
That's AAMS.
Complete Alert Journey (Simplified)
Step 1: Alert Arrives
Monitoring tool raises an alert.
Example:
Disk Utilization on Server ABC = 82%
Salesforce creates a ticket.
AAMS immediately sees it.
Step 2: AAMS Acknowledges Ticket
Instead of waiting for a TSA:
AAMS writes:
Alert acknowledged. Investigation in progress.
This helps meet SLA requirements immediately.
Step 3: AAMS Investigates
AAMS gathers evidence.
It checks:
Logs
Service status
Historical incidents
KB articles
SOPs
RCA documents
Example:
Disk cleanup job runs every night.
Current usage = 82%.
No errors found.
Similar alert closed automatically before.
AAMS builds evidence.
Step 4: AI Makes a Decision
Now AI decides:
Possibility A
False Positive
Example:
Monitoring glitch.
Server healthy.
→ Close ticket
Possibility B
Informational
Example:
CPU spike for 2 minutes.
Returned to normal.
→ Close ticket
Possibility C
Needs Recheck
Example:
Disk Usage = 82%
Not critical yet.
Check again after 60 minutes.
→ Put on Watch Mode
Possibility D
Needs Human
Example:
Production database unavailable.
→ Escalate immediately
The Watch Mode (Actually the Coolest Feature)
Suppose:
Disk usage = 80%
Human today:
Sees alert
Makes note
Remembers to check later
AAMS:
Alert detected
↓
Schedule re-check in 60 mins
↓
Wake up automatically
↓
Check again
If disk becomes:
65%
Close ticket.
If disk becomes:
95%
Escalate immediately.
Nobody has to remember anything.
